{
  "texts": [
    "This metadata falls into two main categories: assay metadata, which encompass technical details like machine type, assay date, and reagent kits, and biological metadata, which describe experimental aspects like sample conditions, exposure to drugs, animal housing conditions, or host genetic information.",
    "The absence of such information may affect downstream statistical analysis and even qualitative interpretation challenging or impossible.",
    "Information about provenance and characteristics of the samples: when it was collected (e.g., date and time), where it was collected from (e.g., latitude, longitude, elevation/depth, site name, country, etc.",
    "), what kind of sample it was (e.g., soil, seawater, feces/stool), and the properties of the environment during collection (e.g., temperature, salinity, pH) or if sample is clinical then phenotypic condition (e.g., age, sex, disease state/normal) from which the sample was taken and the nature of the sample material itself all contribute valuable context to microbial studies (Wood-Charlson et al., 2020; Vangay et al., 2021).",
    "It is subjected to preparation steps for nucleotide sequence analysis or metabolome/metaproteome."
  ]
}